<subSubSection id="C33E44D6FFBFFFFA809028CF36A998B4" pageId="7" pageNumber="38" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B9B175DFFBFFFFA809028CF36A998B4" blockId="7.[136,1452,1594,2017]" pageId="7" pageNumber="38">
<emphasis id="B950CB4FFFBFFFFA809028CF36729995" bold="true" box="[189,356,1702,1728]" pageId="7" pageNumber="38">Comments:—</emphasis>
The stalked sporocarp with wrinkled peridia differs from 
<taxonomicName id="4C246CDEFFBFFFFA83D228CE338A9995" authorityName="H. C. Gilbert" authorityYear="1942" baseAuthorityName="H. C. Gilbert" box="[1023,1180,1702,1728]" class="Myxomycetes" family="Liceaceae" genus="Licea" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Liceales" pageId="7" pageNumber="38" phylum="Mycetozoa" rank="species" species="pedicellata">
<emphasis id="B950CB4FFFBFFFFA83D228CE338A9995" box="[1023,1180,1702,1728]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="38">L. pedicellata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C246CDEFFBFFFFA84F428CE32289995" authorityName="Rex" authorityYear="1890" box="[1241,1342,1703,1728]" class="Myxomycetes" family="Trichiaceae" genus="Trichia" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Trichiales" pageId="7" pageNumber="38" phylum="Mycetozoa" rank="species" species="erecta">
<emphasis id="B950CB4FFFBFFFFA84F428CE32289995" box="[1241,1342,1703,1728]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="38">L. erecta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in that it has dark brown, smooth spores with a thick wall showing a paler thin area. (
<bibRefCitation id="EFB56AACFFBFFFFA83CE28A333D499B1" author="Neubert, H. &amp; Nowotny, W. &amp; Baumann, K." box="[995,1218,1738,1764]" pageId="7" pageNumber="38" refId="ref6056" refString="Neubert, H., Nowotny, W. &amp; Baumann, K. (1993) Die Myxomyceten (Band I). Karlheinz Baumann Verlag Gomaringen." type="book" year="1993">
Neubert 
<emphasis id="B950CB4FFFBFFFFA846B28A2336999B1" box="[1094,1151,1738,1764]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="38">et al.</emphasis>
1993
</bibRefCitation>
). The sporotheca are globose when wet but very wrinkled when dry, with prominent ridges. The spores are similar to those of 
<taxonomicName id="4C246CDEFFBFFFFA8531288632BA985D" authorityName="G. W. Martin" authorityYear="1942" baseAuthorityName="Zukal" box="[1308,1452,1775,1800]" class="Myxomycetes" family="Liceaceae" genus="Licea" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Liceales" pageId="7" pageNumber="38" phylum="Mycetozoa" rank="species" species="parasitica">
<emphasis id="B950CB4FFFBFFFFA8531288632BA985D" box="[1308,1452,1775,1800]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="38">L. parasitica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(11–13(–16) µm diam.), but the thinner area is less pronounced and the spores were completely smooth even when examined by SEM. The wrinkled sporotheca breaking into platelets instead of the lid of 
<taxonomicName id="4C246CDEFFBFFFFA8475295E33F19805" authorityName="G. W. Martin" authorityYear="1942" baseAuthorityName="Zukal" box="[1112,1255,1847,1872]" class="Myxomycetes" family="Liceaceae" genus="Licea" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Liceales" pageId="7" pageNumber="38" phylum="Mycetozoa" rank="species" species="parasitica">
<emphasis id="B950CB4FFFBFFFFA8475295E33F19805" box="[1112,1255,1847,1872]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="38">L. parasitica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
easily avoids any confusion even with sessile specimens. The plasmodium, visible in moist chamber cultures, is thick dull brown and appears as a continuous sludge on the bark surface like many large protoplasmodia combined. The original description of 
<taxonomicName id="4C246CDEFFBFFFFA808B29CA360498E9" box="[166,274,1955,1980]" class="Myxomycetes" family="Liceaceae" genus="Licea" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Liceales" pageId="7" pageNumber="38" phylum="Mycetozoa" rank="species" species="rugosa">
<emphasis id="B950CB4FFFBFFFFA808B29CA360498E9" box="[166,274,1955,1980]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="38">L. rugosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differentiated it from 
<taxonomicName id="4C246CDEFFBFFFFA822729CA35B598E9" authorityName="H. C. Gilbert" authorityYear="1942" baseAuthorityName="H. C. Gilbert" box="[522,675,1954,1980]" class="Myxomycetes" family="Liceaceae" genus="Licea" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Liceales" pageId="7" pageNumber="38" phylum="Mycetozoa" rank="species" species="pedicellata">
<emphasis id="B950CB4FFFBFFFFA822729CA35B598E9" box="[522,675,1954,1980]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="38">L. pedicellata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
on the basis of spore colour being dark brown and the smooth spores (
<bibRefCitation id="EFB56AACFFBFFFFA80BD29AF36A598B4" author="De Basanta, W. D. &amp; Lado, C." box="[144,435,1990,2017]" pageId="7" pageNumber="38" pagination="261 - 314" refId="ref5562" refString="De Basanta, W. D. &amp; Lado, C. (2005) A taxonomic evaluation of the stipitate Licea species. Fungal Diversity 20: 261 - 314." type="journal article" year="2005">De Basanta &amp; Lado 2005</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
